\section{The Sense-And-Trace Protocol}
The goal of the SAT system is to provide a secure privacy preserving distributed tracking system which offers higher tracking accuracies compared to current GSM network based positioning technologies. The SAT system can be used to provide historic or real time tracking.
%The entities for SAT are the mobile phone nodes, the Data Storage Server (DS) and the Certificate Authority (CA).\\

\subsection{SAT System Model}
In the SAT system model there are two types of nodes: i) sensor nodes, and
ii) target nodes. The sensor nodes voluntarily participate in SAT i.e. they run
an application to scan their environment and detect other wireless devices
are in their communication range. The sensor nodes send their logs on the DS (Data Storage) using any data packet service. That is by using a mutually authenticated TCP connection either via a WiFi access point that the sensor node has access to, or by using the cellular data service (e.g. UMTS or HSPDA). The connection between sensor nodes and the DS is encrypted to protect against a global eavesdropper.



Sensor nodes detect other Wifi enabled devices in their vicinity using Wifi passive scanning. When a message is intercepted the sensor node sends a Geolocation Log Message (GLM) to the DS which includes the targets MAC address and the sensor node's location. The DS collects and stores the GLMs for later tracking purposes. .\\
%Phone nodes retrieve a public key from the CA which is used to encrypt the GLM positioning reports before sending it to the DS (see Figure \ref{fig:sat-example}).\\

\newpage

\subsection{System components}
The SAT protocol makes use of the following Components:
\begin{itemize}
\item a DS which is used to store the GLM records
\item the mobile phone nodes which act as distributed detection network
\item a CA which provides the random pseudonym certificates
\end{itemize}

\vspace{0.5cm}
\noindent The CA provides the random pseudonym certificates which are used by the mobile phone nodes to encrypt the GLM records. For each GLM record the phone obtains a new random private key from the CA. The encrypted GLMs are sent to the DS which stores all records for later tracking use. For example in Figure \ref{fig:sat-example} the mobile phone M3 is within range of M2 and M4, therefore M3 will send a GLM for M2 and M4 to the DS. A GLM message includes the transmitting mobile phone's location, the date \& time, and the detected MAC addresses. The location data inside the GLM is encrypted using random public keys provided by the CA for privacy preservation. The location information inside the GLM is the only content inside the GLM which is encrypted.\\
\begin{comment}
Each time the scanning phone detects a target it will report the target and send it's own location along with it. The DS collects all reported detections of the tracking target. Using the reported data it is possible to compute the movements of the target without the need of any stationary infrastructure.\\
\end{comment}

