\subsection{Target logging}
A node detects all Wifi MAC (BSSID) addresses by passive scanning all Wifi communications every 15 seconds (the ScanningInterval) in its area. The node subsequently sends the detected MAC addresses as a GLM to the DS. A GLM report includes the following information:

\begin{itemize}
 \item 32 bit integer as Latitude (encrypted)
 \item 32 bit integer as Longitude (encrypted)
 \item 46 bit Wifi BSSID MAC address of the target detected. one or more
 \item 128 bit integer as public key identifier
 \item 40 bit time stamp
\end{itemize}

\vspace{0.5cm}
Each GLM has its position location encrypted using a new random public key obtained from the CA (see Figure \ref{fig:sat-example}). Since the location details inside the GLM are encrypted the DS cannot use the GLMs for tracking without obtaining the decyption keys for the GLMs.


\subsection{Target tracing}
In order for the LEA to trace a target using SAT, they need to first obtain authorisation and the decryption keys. This is due to the pseydonym public key infrastructure (PPKI) which is used to encrypt the position locatio inside the GLM. Figure \ref{fig:sat-comm} shows the communication model and agent interactions. The smartphones scan and sense other smartphones and transmit a location report (GLM) to the server (Step 1 \& 2). In Step 3 the LEA asks for tracking authorisation, which goes to an Auhority which has to approve/deny the request in Step 4. Once approved the DS will transmit the target's GLM records to the CA for decryption (Step 5). The CA returns the decrypted records which then allows the LEA to compute the positioning data for the target.\\



The server then takes multiple reports for the same Wifi MAC addresses and using the GLM reports to calculate the target positions. The positions are calculated in for example 60 seconds intervals, also referred to as \texttt{Delta} and positioning interval in this thesis.\\





