\section{Simulation results}
\subsection{Tracking accuracy results}
The \texttt{Delta} variable is the time interval which is used to aggregate witness reports to compute the location of a tracked target. In other words it could also be called a Positioning Interval, because in these intervals the positions are calculated. The \texttt{Delta} variable, for which we used 30 and 60 seconds in our simulations, has no influence on the average tracking deviation (Figure \ref{fig:delta-timegap-deviation}). This result is explained by the simulation setup. In our simulation slow moving pedestrians are simulated. If we


However a \texttt{Delta} of 60 seconds reduces the tracking gaps while not having any negative impact on the tracking accuracy (Figure \ref{fig:scanninginterval-timegap}). Since we simulate walking pedestrians, which are slow moving targets compared to for example cars, aggregating the data of 60 seconds does not decrease the tracking accuracy. If the target were a fast moving object i.e. a car, the difference between \texttt{Delta} 30 and 60 would be more noticeable showing a decrease in accuracy.\\
A tracking gap is the biggest gap between two triangulations. A \texttt{Delta} of 60 reduces the tracking gaps, since it allows for more witness accounts to be used for each triangulation. If for any given \texttt{Delta} there are 2 or less witness reports, the data is discarded and no triangulation is computed. This makes it possible for the tracking gaps to exist. The tracking gaps are at night when the simulated population is ``at home''. The UDel Model simulator simulates the typical urban commuting traffic. Which means during the day, due to the increased population amount inside the city, there are fewer tracking gaps, if any.\\



Higher \texttt{ScanningInterval} values increase tracking gaps. This doesn't come as a surprise as a higher \texttt{ScanningInterval} means we have less witness reports for a given \texttt{Delta}. For a valid triangulation we require at least three witnesses, if only 2 witnesses observed the target during a \texttt{Delta} interval the positioning data is discarded. An algorithm that is flexible towards the amount of witness reports can use more advanced heuristics to adapt between many reports and very few witness reports.\\

