\subsection{Bandwidth requirement results}
In this section we discuss the the bandwidth requirements of the SAT protocol.
We investigate the bandwidth requirements for the various \texttt{ScanningInterval} values we used.\\

\noindent The biggest influence on bandwidth usage is the \texttt{ScanningInterval} variable.
It directly relates to how many reports are sent to the DS and how much outgoing bandwidth is used by the SAT protocol.

A GLM report sent by a node to the DS contains the following data:
\begin{itemize}
 \item 32 bit integer as Latitude (encrypted)
 \item 32 bit integer as Longitude (encrypted)
 \item 46 bit Wifi BSSID MAC address of the target detected. one or more
 \item 128 bit integer as public key identifier
 \item 40 bit time stamp
\end{itemize}
This gives us in total a payload of 288 bits per message, excluding encryption.
The location information of the payload data is encrypted using the public key obtained from the CA
and the actual payload size increases. Using Eliptic Curve Cryptography (ECC) together 1024 bit keys  results in a netto payload of eight kilobytes after the GPS coordinates have been encrypted. The 8 kilobytes already include a 10\% added overhead to account for TCP/IP overhead.



